{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is at the module handoff boundary (request builder -> API client). A unit test of only the formatter can miss wiring/serialization omissions, while an in-process fake API client can catch the real failure without real network/OS. System is rejected because real HTTP is not required; Agentic is rejected because correctness does not depend on model output.","test_description":"Wire the classifier module with a fake API transport that records outbound payloads. Invoke classify() with a taxonomy, then assert the sent request contains every allowed label exactly as expected in the API-facing field.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic normalization/validation logic that can be reproduced at one local function/object boundary with fixed input. Integration is rejected by behavior text 'API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy': the same condition is fully reproducible by passing that raw label into the normalization path directly.","test_description":"Call the normalization/result-mapping function with a fixture response containing an out-of-taxonomy label (e.g., 'medical') and assert output is exactly 'unknown'.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Pure determinism/idempotence of normalization. No module interaction, I/O, or model behavior is needed to reproduce failures.","test_description":"Invoke normalization multiple times with the exact same raw response payload and assert all outputs are identical.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on repeated live model decisions and potential non-determinism in provider outputs. A stub would hide this failure mode. Workflow is rejected because this is repeated single-step classification, not a multi-stage agent pipeline with distinct model decisions across stages.","test_description":"Run N repeated real provider calls for identical document+taxonomy, record raw provider outputs and final labels, and assert label variance only occurs when raw provider response changes (otherwise labels stay consistent).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure boundary is orchestration between token-budget logic and dispatch. A pure unit test of tokenizer/policy can miss ordering bugs (dispatch happening before enforcement). Real OS/network is unnecessary; fake transport suffices.","test_description":"Configure a small budget and a fake API client. Submit an oversized document and assert behavior matches policy (truncate or reject) and that any dispatched payload is within budget; if reject policy, assert no dispatch call occurs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Needs a real provider call and real HTTP/API behavior to validate provider-reported usage; local fakes cannot expose estimator-vs-provider accounting drift. Agentic is rejected by behavior text: this checks usage metadata budget compliance, not model output quality/decision correctness.","test_description":"Execute a real API call with a representative document and taxonomy, read provider-reported usage tokens from response metadata, and assert reported usage <= configured per-call budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.17,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure is retry orchestration across classifier + API client + backoff policy. In-process fake API responses (e.g., 429 then success) and controllable clock are sufficient; real OS/network/subprocess is not required. Agentic is rejected because no dependence on model output content.","test_description":"Use a fake API client scripted to return rate-limit error then success. Invoke classify(), assert module performs wait/backoff and retry calls, and returns successful label instead of surfacing the first error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
